Final Project: Which of the 50 states should you climb in?¶

Introduction¶

Climbing gyms are a growing phenomenon and are especially popular amongst computer science students and professionals. Indoor rock climbing and bouldering are more accessible. Climbing gyms provide the majority of the necessary equipment as well as the convenience of a 30-minute commute to the facility and back. It does, however, lack a certain risk-taking thrill that outdoor climbing on the sides of mountains can only provide.
Rock climbing has been a long tradition of mountaineering and while traditionally done with a rope and protection, free soloing is an especially bold style of climbing. There are so many types of rock climbing. Just to name a few that this data science project will explore there are traditional, sport, toprope, boulder, ice, aid, mixed, and alpine.

Trad/Traditional:
any climbing that involves removable gear after the pitch is complete
Sport:
any climbing using fixed protection, as opposed to trad climbing
Toprope:
rock climbing where climbers are supported by a rope that runs down a rock face
Boulder:
a style of climbing close to the ground without ropes and with crash mattresses
Ice:
essentially rock climbing, but on ice
Aid:
often used on very long, multi-day routes (big walls) and is where climbers use gear to help ascension
Mixed:
a combination of ice climbing and rock climbing often requires specialized gear
Alpine:
branch of climbing in which the main objective is often to reach the summit of a mountain

As we can see, there are so many types of rock climbing. Where should one even begin to look? The 50 states have a lot to offer in terms of climbing. Each state has its own set of climbing problems to be solved. But, which state is best for ice climbing? For beginners? For variety? For expert boulderers looking for grade V11 and up?

This data science project will aim to detail the perfect state for every climber based off of climbing type, quantity, and difficulty.

Gathering Dataset 1: Types of Climbing in the US¶

The data in this project will be from https://www.mountainproject.com/route-guide.
Mountain Project is a website that serves as a guidebook to more than 170,000 climbing routes across the world and we will be using it for our exploration of US climbing. This specific link is a web page that houses a climbing directory for each of the 50 states. These directories are hyperlinked on this page. Rather than manually clicking and saving each of the 50 links, I will be scraping them off the web page and storing them in a dictionary structure. A more detailed explanation of the process will be included as we proceed.

df2 = pd.DataFrame() # Dataframe that will hold ['State', 'Latitude', 'Longitude']

for state, l in state_links.items():
    webpage = requests.get(l) # get data for each state's webpage from the state_links list
    soup = BeautifulSoup(webpage.content, 'html.parser')
    
    coordinates = []
    
    for c in soup.find_all('table', class_="description-details"):
        coor = soup.find('td', text = 'GPS:').find_next_sibling('td').text
        coordinates.append(coor) 
        # print(coor)
        
    coordinates = [s.split('\n') for s in coordinates]
    
    c1 = pd.DataFrame(data = coordinates)
    c1['State'] = state
    df2 = pd.concat([df2, c1])

Each of the states has information about the number of each type of climbing (Trad, Sport, Toprope, Boulder, Ice, Aid, Mixed, Alpine) on their web pages. The following will extract the number of each type of climbing for each state and put them into a DataFrame. This information, unlike the coordinates, was harder to find since it is not explicitly visible on the web page itself.
However, using the Chrome Inspect tool I found that each of the climbing areas linked on the state's web page has a list of the number of each type of climb that they hold and can be located with the tag <span class="lef-nav-[Insert Climb Type]" and so I will be gathering all of those into a DataFrame.

This portion also utilizes pivot tables. Pivot tables are a quick way to summarize large amounts of data. Since each state will produce a huge DataFrame of each area's count for the type f climbing it is currently a massive mess. The pivot table will allow us to take the sum of each type of climb.

For more information on pivot tables click here: https://www.machinelearningplus.com/pandas/pandas-pivot-table-in-python/

In [10]:
df = pd.DataFrame() # will hold the number of each climb type
types = ['Trad','Sport','Toprope','Boulder','Ice','Aid','Mixed','Alpine']

for state, l in state_links.items():
    webpage = requests.get(l)
    soup = BeautifulSoup(webpage.content, 'html.parser')
    
    num = []
    ts = []

    for type in types:
        for n in soup.find_all('span', class_ = "lef-nav-" + type):
            num.append(n.text)
            ts.append(type)
    
    # Clean up the data strings and convert counts into ints
    num = [s.strip() for s in num]
    num = [s.replace(',','') for s in num]
    num = [s.replace(' /','') for s in num]
    num = map(int, num)
    
    stuff = pd.DataFrame(data = num)
    stuff['Climb Type'] = ts
    stuff['State'] = state
    
    table = stuff.pivot_table(columns = 'Climb Type', index = 'State', aggfunc = np.sum)
    # display(table)
    df = pd.concat([df, table])

Gathering Dataset 2: Climbing Grades in the US¶

Now that I have created some tools for climbers to figure out which states to go to for a specific type of climbing, I want to delve into the best state for the different climbing grades. Climbs are rated on either a rock climbing scale. Typically, climbing grades do fall into a rudimentary scale of difficulty. A 5.0 to 5.7 is considered easy, 5.8 to 5.10 is considered intermediate, 5.11 to 5.12 is hard, and 5.13 to 5.15 is reserved for a very elite few. Bouldering problems are rated on a different scale. This system ranges from V0 to V16, with V0 considered to be easy and V16 saved for the elite.

In order to do this, I am going to scrape climbing grades and quantity for each of the states using the same hyperlinks that I collected in the previous sections. This was again, slightly challenging since this information wasn't in an easily identifiable table and instead I found it inside a variable of an embedded script on the webpage. I first grabbed the entire string and then processed it to be the strings ["rating", "count"] for each state. Also, since rock climbing and bouldering follow different ratings, I will be makings two different DataFrames.

In [21]:
ratings = pd.DataFrame() # will hold the scraped and split strings of rock and boulder [grade, count]

for state, l in state_links.items():
    x = []
    webpage = requests.get(l)
    soup = BeautifulSoup(webpage.content, 'html.parser')
    
    c = soup.find_all('script', {'type':'text/javascript'})
    c = c[6].string.split('var data = {')
    c = c[1].split(';')
    c = c[0]
    c = c.split('"boulder"')
    
    x.append({'state':state, 'rock':c[0], 'boulder':c[1]})
    d = pd.DataFrame(x)

    ratings = pd.concat([ratings, d])

ratings = ratings.sort_values('state')
ratings = ratings.reset_index()
ratings = ratings.drop(labels='index', axis=1)
# ratings
In [22]:
rcs = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['Rating', 'Count'])  # will hold the final processed list of Rock Climbing ratings and counts for each state
i = 0
for r in ratings['rock']:
    curr = []
    state = (ratings.at[i, 'state'])
    i = i+1
    x = r.split('"rock":[')
    x = x[1].split('],')
    for s in x:
        rc = s.split(',"')
        u = rc[0].split("', '")
        y = u[0].split(',')
        # display(y[1])
        
        yw = y[0].split('["')
        
        if len(yw)==2:
            yw = yw[1].replace('"', '')
            curr.append({'state':state, 'Rating':yw, 'Count':y[1]})
        else:
            curr.append({'state':state, 'Rating':yw[0], 'Count':y[1]})

        temp = pd.DataFrame(curr)
        rcs = pd.concat([rcs, temp])
        
        
rcs = rcs[['state', 'Rating', 'Count']]
rcs = rcs.drop_duplicates(keep='first')
rcs = rcs.reset_index()

rcs2 = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['Rating', 'Count'])  # Bouldering rating and counts
i = 0
for r in ratings['boulder']:
    curr = []
    state = (ratings.at[i, 'state'])
    i = i+1
    x = r.split(':[')
    x = x[1].split('],')
    for s in x:
        rc = s.split(',"')
        u = rc[0].split("', '")
        y = u[0].split(',')
        # display(y)
        
        yw = y[0].split('["')
        
        if len(yw)==2:
            yw = yw[1].replace('"', '')
            curr.append({'state':state, 'Rating':yw, 'Count':y[1]})
        else:
            curr.append({'state':state, 'Rating':yw[0], 'Count':y[0]})

        temp2 = pd.DataFrame(curr)
        rcs2 = pd.concat([rcs2, temp2])

pyplot.ylabel("Problem Count")
pyplot.title("Rock Climbing Grade Count in CA, CO, AZ, UT, WA")
pyplot.show()

This plot is showing the total counts for each climbing grade. It is interesting to see that even regardless of California having the most number of climbs total, Colorado still has more of 5.12 and up rock climbing problems.

Conclusion¶

I set out on this tutorial to try to find the ideal state for every type of climber, but I think I've ended with a few tools that could help the climber identify their perfect state themselves.
As an example, let's say that our friend Matt is a climber that is really into bouldering and toproping. He just started rock climbing so he currently climbs 5.7 grade problems. However, he's been bouldering for quite awhile so he can climb anything up until a V9.
For his climbing interests, our correlation matrix shows that bouldering and toproping have a 92% correlation and so, a state with good bouldering opportunities will likely have good toproping opporunities and vice versa. Then, we have a DataFrame that shows the top ten states for each type fo climbing. We can use this in conjunction to the plots above to see which state will be optimal. Since he's just started rock climbing, I immediately notice Washington state having many climbs that are rated 5.7 in comparison to the other top 5 states. Washington also has a fair amount of V1-V8 problems in comparison to the other plotted states. Washington is also in the top 10 states for both bouldering and toproping.
Matt's ideal climbing state appears to be Washington!
